---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import RelatedLinks from '../components/RelatedLinks.astro';
import SolderedFlowDiagram from '../components/diagrams/SolderedFlowDiagram.astro';

/*
  SOLDERED-STORAGE landing page, targets "wipe laptop soldered SSD" / "erase
  soldered storage".

  COPY verbatim from content/articles/proofwipe-soldered-storage.md (owner's
  voice, do not rewrite). Layout + SEO only. Edits: typographic quotes and the
  two requested links: closing proofwipe.com -> /download, and "our guide to
  wiping and reselling workstations" -> /guides/wipe-and-resell-workstations.
  NOTE: keep {' '} before inline links, since Astro collapses newline-only whitespace.
*/

const title = 'How to wipe a laptop with soldered SSD / storage';
const description =
  'Can’t remove the drive? Here’s how to securely wipe a laptop with soldered storage (Surface and modern ultrabooks included) in place, with no disassembly. Boot from USB and run a verified NIST 800-88 firmware Purge on the soldered SSD, with a certificate to prove it.';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'How to securely wipe a laptop with soldered storage',
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'ProofWipe' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'ProofWipe', url: 'https://proofwipe.com' },
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://proofwipe.com/wipe-laptop-soldered-storage',
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd} ogType="article" ogImage="/og/wipe-laptop-soldered-storage.png">
  <article class="container-page py-14 lg:py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent">Guide</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
        How to securely wipe a laptop with soldered storage
      </h1>

      <div class="prose-pw mt-8 space-y-5 text-[1.0625rem] leading-relaxed text-muted">
        <p>
          More and more laptops ship with the storage soldered directly to the motherboard. Many
          ultrabooks, most Microsoft Surface devices, and a growing number of business laptops no
          longer have a drive you can unscrew and pull out. That breaks the old way of disposing of
          machines securely, so here is how to handle it.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Why soldered storage is a problem for disposal</h2>
        <p>
          For years the secure-disposal routine was simple: remove the drive and shred it. When the
          storage is soldered on, you cannot remove it without destroying the whole machine. So you
          are left with two bad options. Physically destroy a perfectly good laptop just to kill
          the data, throwing away its resale and reuse value. Or hand it on and hope the
          &ldquo;delete and reformat&rdquo; you did is enough, which it is not, because deleted and
          reformatted data is easy to recover.
        </p>
        <p>
          Neither is acceptable if the machine held business, client, or personal data.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">The answer: wipe the storage in place</h2>
        <p>
          You do not need to remove soldered storage to securely erase it. You sanitize it right
          where it sits, using the drive's own firmware, and you get a record proving it was done.
        </p>
        <SolderedFlowDiagram />
        <p>
          The approach is the same one you would use to wipe any machine's own drive. Build a
          bootable USB stick with a wiping tool. Boot the laptop from the stick instead of its
          operating system. Run a firmware sanitize, NIST 800-88 Purge, which tells the soldered
          SSD's own controller to erase its entire flash. Verify it by reading the drive back. Save
          the certificate.
        </p>
        <p>
          No disassembly, no shredding, no destroyed hardware. The data is gone, the laptop still
          works and still has resale value, and you have proof.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Why firmware Purge is the right method here</h2>
        <p>
          Soldered storage is almost always flash, an SSD or an NVMe module. Overwriting flash from
          the outside can leave data behind in the spare areas that wear-leveling uses. A firmware
          Purge, using the drive's built-in NVMe Sanitize or Secure Erase command, erases the whole
          thing, including those areas, and it does it in minutes. It is both the most thorough and
          the fastest option for exactly the kind of storage that gets soldered on.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Do it with ProofWipe</h2>
        <p>
          ProofWipe boots from a USB stick, runs a verified NIST 800-88 Purge on the machine's own
          soldered drive, and writes a tamper-evident certificate you can keep or hand off. It
          protects the drive it is running from, so you cannot wipe the wrong thing, and there are
          no per-drive fees. Get it at{' '}
          <a href="/download" class="font-medium text-accent hover:underline">proofwipe.com</a>,
          and see the full walkthrough in{' '}
          <a href="/guides/wipe-and-resell-workstations" class="font-medium text-accent hover:underline"
            >our guide to wiping and reselling workstations</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <RelatedLinks links={['/nist-800-88-clear-vs-purge', '/guides/wipe-and-resell-workstations', '/verify']} />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
